===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|wanten||to lack|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|non}} {{term|vanta||to lack|lang=non}}, from {{proto|Germanic|wanatōnan|to be wanting, lack|lang=en}}, from {{proto|Germanic|title=|wanô|lack, deficiency|lang=en}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|(e)wAn-||wān-|empty|lang=en}}. Cognate with {{etyl|gmh|-}} {{term|wan||not full, empty|lang=gmh}}, {{etyl|dum|-}} {{term|wan||empty, poor|lang=dum}}, {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|wana||want, lack, absence, deficiency|lang=ang}}. See {{l|en|wan}}.

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{transitive}} To [[wish]] for or to [[desire]] (something). {{defdate|from 18th c.}}
#: ''What do you '''want''' to eat?''
#: ''I '''want''' you to leave.''
#: ''I never '''wanted''' to go back to live with my mother.''
#: ''I '''want''' to be an astronaut when I'm older''
#: ''I don't '''want''' him to marry Gloria, I '''want''' him to marry me!''
#: ''What do you '''want''' from me?''
#: ''Do you '''want''' anything from the shops?''
# {{intransitive|now|_|dated}} To be [[lacking]], not to exist. {{defdate|from 13th c.}}
#: ''There was something '''wanting''' in the play.''
# {{transitive}} To [[lack]], not to have (something). {{defdate|from 13th c.}}
#* '''1621''', Robert Burton, ''The Anatomy of Melancholy'', II.3.7:
#*: he that hath skill to be a pilot '''wants''' a ship; and he that could govern a commonwealth [...] '''wants''' means to exercise his worth, hath not a poor office to manage.
# {{transitive|[[colloquial]]ly with [[verbal noun]] as object}} To be in need of; to [[require]] (something). {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
#: ''That chair '''wants''' fixing.''
#* '''1922''', {{w|Virginia Woolf}}, ''{{w|Jacob's Room}}'' Chapter 2
#*: The mowing-machine always '''wanted''' oiling. Barnet turned it under Jacob's window, and it creaked—creaked, and rattled across the lawn and creaked again.

